#week-title("Two", "The Menstruum & The Cotton Wick Test")

=== Core Teaching

The choice and quality of the *menstruum* (the solvent used for extraction) is
critical. For maximum potency, the ideal liquid is the distilled water taken
from the plant itself. However, rectified spirit of wine (high-proof alcohol) is
the practical and valid alternative for most students.

Before using any spirit for extraction, you must verify its strength using the
*Cotton Wick Test*. This is non-negotiable — impure or diluted menstruum is one
of the primary causes of failed preparations.

#doctrine[
  _"The Cotton Wick Test: Dip a cotton wick into the spirit and set it alight. If
  the flame fastens on the wick itself and burns it cleanly, the spirit is
  sufficiently dephlegmated. If it does not hold the flame on the wick, the
  alcohol is too dilute and must be rectified further."_
  #align(right)[— HAB (Bartlett Prima transcript)]
]

=== Topics This Week

- The Ideal Menstruum: plant water vs. spirits of wine
- The Seven-Fold Distillation method for rectifying brandy
- Dephlegmation: removing excess water from alcohol
- The Cotton Wick Test protocol

#inner-work[
  *Consecrating the Laboratory Space*

  Sit in silence within your laboratory space for at least twenty minutes this
  week. Bring nothing but your attention.

  Ask yourself honestly: What am I bringing into this space? What intention am I
  carrying into the Work? The laboratory and the meditation space are the same
  Work operating through two hands. Consecrate the space with your willed
  sincerity.
]

